:"19 September 1200","1207":"1207","Body lost or destroyed":"Body, Petit-Trou-de-Nippes, Anse-à-Veau, Nippes, Haiti","Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire,England":"Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire, England":"Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire, England","England":"England","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sancto","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: nickname from Latin  <i>sanctus</i> ‘holy, sainted’, denoting a pious person.  Compare  Saint  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Saint","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cyr, Remy.","English and French: nickname for a particularly pious individual, from Old French and Middle English <i>saint(e)</i>, <i>seint(e)</i> ‘holy’ (from Latin <i>sanctus</i> ‘blameless, holy’). The vocabulary word was occasionally used in the Middle Ages as a personal name and this may have given rise to some instances of the surname.","English: perhaps a nickname for someone who wore, made, or sold girdles, from Middle English <i>ceint</i>, <i>seint</i>, <i>saint</i> ‘girdle’ (Old French <i>ceint</i>, Latin <i>cinctum</i>). Compare   Center  ."]}]},{"name":"Paulo","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luiz, Adelino, Alfredo, Ana, Herminio, Justino, Albino, Alipio, Americo, Angelina, Arnaldo.  Portuguese Joaquim, Paulo.","Portuguese and Spanish: from the personal name <i>Paulo</i>, from Latin <i>Paulus</i> (see   Paul  ).","In some cases also Breton, from a pet form of the personal name   Paul  , or southern French, from a regional variant of the same personal name."],"variants":[{"name":"Paul","meanings":["English, French, German, Dutch, Swedish, West Indian (mainly Haiti, also e.g. Saint Lucia), and African (mainly Nigeria and Tanzania): from the personal name <i>Paul</i> (from Latin <i>Paulus</i> ‘small’), which has always been popular in Christendom. It was the name adopted by the Pharisee Saul of Tarsus after his conversion to Christianity on the road to Damascus in about  AD  34. He was a most energetic missionary to the Gentiles in the Roman Empire, and played a very significant role in establishing Christianity as a major world religion. The name was borne also by numerous other early Christian saints. It is also occasionally borne by Jews; the reasons for this are not clear. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages and their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Greek   Pavlis  , Slovenian   Pavel   and <b>Pavlič</b> (see   Pavlic  ), Polish <b>Paweł</b> (see   Pawel  ) and   Pawlicki  , Assyrian/Chaldean   Polous   and   Polus  . In France, this surname is most common in Brittany (see 2 below).","Breton (mainly Finistère): from a Frenchified form of the personal name <i>Paol</i>, Breton form of   Paul  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Phóil</b> ‘son of Paul’. Compare   McFall  ."]}]},{"name":"raph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"raph de Sancto Paulo was born in 1140, in Normandy, France. He had at least 3 daughters with Mahaut Matilde de Clermont. He died in 1207, in Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire, England, at the age of 67, and was buried in Body, Petit-Trou-de-Nippes, Anse-à-Veau, Nippes, Haiti."},"et":{"1140–1207":"1140–1207","1140–1200":"1140–1200","1175–1285":"1175–1285","1177–Female":"1177–Surnud","1179–Female":"1179–Surnud","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1177":"1177","1175":"1175","1285":"1285","1140":"1140","about 1179":"umbes 1179","about 1177":"umbes 1177","19 September 1200":"19. september 1200","1207":"1207","Body lost or destroyed":"Body, Petit-Trou-de-Nippes, Anse-à-Veau, Nip, Haiti","Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire,England":"Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire, England":"Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire, England","England":"England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1140–1207":"1140–1207","1140–1200":"1140–1200","1175–1285":"1175–1285","1177–Female":"1177–Kuollut","1179–Female":"1179–Kuollut","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1177":"1177","1175":"1175","1285":"1285","1140":"1140","about 1179":"noin 1179","about 1177":"noin 1177","19 September 1200":"19. syyskuuta 1200","1207":"1207","Body lost or destroyed":"Body, Petit-Trou-de-Nippes, Anse-à-Veau, Nip, Haiti","Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire,England":"Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire, England":"Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire, Engla